1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:02,425
<i>Previously on</i> Prison Break...

2
00:00:02,722 --> 00:00:03,722
We're staying.

3
00:00:04,755 --> 00:00:05,785
Give 'em hell.

4
00:00:13,661 --> 00:00:14,772
Bill, don't do this.

5
00:00:14,815 --> 00:00:17,592
<i>I've dedicated my life to this country.
To President Reynolds.</i>

6
00:00:17,698 --> 00:00:20,244
Every photo, every file,
get rid of it all.

7
00:00:20,386 --> 00:00:21,647
<i>Bill, don't do this.</i>

8
00:00:21,954 --> 00:00:23,927
You left a message for Mr. Geary.

9
00:00:23,975 --> 00:00:25,642
<i>I'm going to gut you, bow to stern.</i>

10
00:00:25,725 --> 00:00:27,311
I did not kill Roy Geary.

11
00:00:27,474 --> 00:00:28,474
Bagwell set me up!

12
00:00:28,597 --> 00:00:29,424
You are under arrest

13
00:00:29,425 --> 00:00:31,534
for the first degree murder
of Roy William Geary.

14
00:00:31,552 --> 00:00:34,035
My therapist said
that I need to confront you

15
00:00:34,351 --> 00:00:36,351
to let you know how betrayed I feel.

16
00:00:38,162 --> 00:00:39,662
This is the Tribune Police!

17
00:00:40,040 --> 00:00:42,915
Look, as long as you do your job,
we forget about Shales.

18
00:00:42,974 --> 00:00:46,394
And then you can go back to Colorado
and visit your son and family.

19
00:00:48,246 --> 00:00:50,360
Don't you ever mention his name again.

20
00:00:50,417 --> 00:00:52,073
What about your friend back there?

21
00:00:52,142 --> 00:00:53,697
If we're going to go down...

22
00:00:54,573 --> 00:00:56,127
might as well go down swinging.

23
00:01:13,081 --> 00:01:14,159
Almost made it.

24
00:01:19,020 --> 00:01:20,247
<i>- Is that you?</i>
- Get up.

25
00:01:24,580 --> 00:01:25,580
Turn around.

26
00:01:26,642 --> 00:01:27,642
Turn around!

27
00:01:27,985 --> 00:01:29,523
If you're going to murder us, Alex,

28
00:01:29,570 --> 00:01:31,618
you'll have to look us
in the eyes while you do it.

29
00:01:31,666 --> 00:01:33,749
- Shut up.
- You want me, you got me.

30
00:01:33,978 --> 00:01:35,188
Let my brother go!

31
00:01:35,269 --> 00:01:36,480
I don't want either of you.

32
00:01:36,490 --> 00:01:38,238
I just want my life back!

33
00:01:38,571 --> 00:01:40,793
You're going to kill two innocent men
to get it, huh?

34
00:01:40,794 --> 00:01:41,794
Absolutely.

35
00:01:42,305 --> 00:01:44,665
<i>This is the United States Border Patrol.</i>

36
00:01:44,700 --> 00:01:46,943
<i>Drop the weapon
and remain where you are.</i>

37
00:01:48,007 --> 00:01:49,502
<i>Drop your weapon.</i>

38
00:01:49,936 --> 00:01:51,482
United States Border Patrol.

39
00:01:51,674 --> 00:01:53,138
Drop your weapon!

40
00:01:57,038 --> 00:01:59,157
I'm FBI. These men are in my custody.

41
00:01:59,227 --> 00:02:00,615
I don't care who you are.

42
00:02:00,726 --> 00:02:03,504
Until we verify,
you will drop your weapon

43
00:02:03,505 --> 00:02:04,860
or we will drop you.

44
00:02:05,416 --> 00:02:06,416
Your choice.

45
00:02:19,988 --> 00:02:20,988
Move in!

46
00:02:22,897 --> 00:02:24,512
Hands on your head, now!

47
00:02:26,463 --> 00:02:27,492
Don't move!

48
00:02:34,213 --> 00:02:35,733
You got anything to drink?

49
00:02:36,601 --> 00:02:37,642
Check the back.

50
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:41,371
<i>Unknown rider, unknown rider,
this is DEA on guard.</i>

51
00:02:41,791 --> 00:02:43,502
<i>Bring up frequency 1145.</i>

52
00:02:48,501 --> 00:02:49,546
What do you mean "Oh oh"?

53
00:02:49,581 --> 00:02:51,366
Border Patrol's on our ass, man.

54
00:02:52,676 --> 00:02:54,094
How long till we get to Mexico?

55
00:02:54,175 --> 00:02:55,841
We're already in Mexico, Papi.

56
00:02:56,050 --> 00:02:57,467
I thought they couldn't follow us

57
00:02:57,524 --> 00:02:59,837
- once we crossed the border.
- Not since 9/11, hombre.

58
00:03:00,426 --> 00:03:02,555
<i>I repeat: unknown rider,
unknown...</i>

59
00:03:02,615 --> 00:03:04,070
What are we going to do?

60
00:03:05,235 --> 00:03:07,030
Pull the chord, and pray.

61
00:03:07,863 --> 00:03:08,863
Oh, hell no!

62
00:03:09,249 --> 00:03:12,190
Look, we try and land the plane,
we're pinched for sure.

63
00:03:12,674 --> 00:03:13,674
And if we jump?

64
00:03:14,363 --> 00:03:16,251
We're in the middle of the desert.

65
00:03:16,925 --> 00:03:19,805
Patrol have a hard time
trying to find us once we land.

66
00:03:19,864 --> 00:03:20,968
If we land.

67
00:03:21,455 --> 00:03:22,840
Oh, you're going to land.

68
00:03:22,862 --> 00:03:24,576
It's just a matter of how hard.

69
00:03:25,719 --> 00:03:26,780
Good luck, amigo.

70
00:03:44,687 --> 00:03:46,746
<i>We're receiving reports
that escaped convicts</i>

71
00:03:46,789 --> 00:03:49,083
<i>Lincoln Burrows and Michael Scofield</i>

72
00:03:49,186 --> 00:03:52,687
<i>have been apprehended a few miles
north of the US-Mexican border.</i>

73
00:03:52,763 --> 00:03:54,991
<i>Federal Agent Alex Mahone
with assistance</i>

74
00:03:54,992 --> 00:03:57,021
<i>from the United States Border Patrol</i>

75
00:03:57,061 --> 00:03:59,727
<i>took the men into custody
just a short time ago.</i>

76
00:03:59,875 --> 00:04:01,997
<i>Now, not a lot of information
available at this time,</i>

77
00:04:02,042 --> 00:04:04,684
<i>but we do know the brothers
were apprehended without incident</i>

78
00:04:04,747 --> 00:04:08,122
<i>while attempting to leave the country
through the deserts of New Mexico,</i>

79
00:04:08,123 --> 00:04:10,865
<i>quite a long way from Illinois's
Fox River State Penitentiary,</i>

80
00:04:10,905 --> 00:04:13,485
<i>where they escaped
from less than ten days ago.</i>

81
00:04:13,810 --> 00:04:14,840
<i>The Fox River Eight,</i>

82
00:04:14,841 --> 00:04:16,747
<i>as the group of convicts
were once known,</i>

83
00:04:16,748 --> 00:04:18,176
<i>are now down to four,</i>

84
00:04:18,312 --> 00:04:20,312
<i>as only Benjamin Miles Franklin,</i>

85
00:04:20,393 --> 00:04:25,029
<i>Fernando Sucre, Charles Patoshik
and Theodore Bagwell remain at large.</i>

86
00:04:25,312 --> 00:04:27,080
<i>- Officials say that...</i>
- Sir.

87
00:04:27,122 --> 00:04:28,247
He just heard.

88
00:04:28,311 --> 00:04:29,627
And he'd like to see you.

90
00:04:35,992 --> 00:04:37,777
<i>... known, are now down to four,</i>

91
00:04:37,899 --> 00:04:39,832
<i>as only Benjamin Miles Franklin,</i>

92
00:04:39,901 --> 00:04:44,369
<i>Fernando Sucre, Charles Patoshik
and Theodore Bagwell remain at large.</i>

93
00:04:44,421 --> 00:04:45,857
Godspeed, gentlemen.

94
00:05:08,978 --> 00:05:10,105
'Scuse me, Sarge.

95
00:05:11,526 --> 00:05:14,106
I... was wondering if you could...
help a brother out.

96
00:05:14,152 --> 00:05:15,152
With what?

97
00:05:16,173 --> 00:05:20,004
I only recently returned
from delivering democracy to the desert

98
00:05:20,085 --> 00:05:22,600
and uh, I was wondering if

99
00:05:23,313 --> 00:05:24,848
you could tell me how a guy goes about

100
00:05:24,871 --> 00:05:27,290
getting a hold
of one of those prosthetic jobbies.

101
00:05:28,054 --> 00:05:30,637
What, they make you whole
before they shipped you back?

102
00:05:30,662 --> 00:05:32,681
Well, let's just say
the doctor made the bed.

103
00:05:32,705 --> 00:05:34,760
He just neglected to tuck in the sheets.

104
00:05:36,484 --> 00:05:39,587
Best thing for you to do
is go on down there to VA. Get in line.

105
00:05:40,900 --> 00:05:41,900
That simple?

106
00:05:44,650 --> 00:05:47,587
Till they send you the bill
and you got to figure out how to pay.

107
00:05:47,667 --> 00:05:49,347
Those bastards in Washington send us off

108
00:05:49,394 --> 00:05:51,837
to fight for them;
not a damn one of 'em fights for us.

109
00:05:51,838 --> 00:05:52,949
And that is a crime.

110
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:56,098
But luckily for me...

111
00:05:58,025 --> 00:05:59,302
money is not the issue.

112
00:06:00,150 --> 00:06:01,025
Is that right?

113
00:06:01,026 --> 00:06:04,789
Any particular, uh,
forms I might need in order to qualify?

114
00:06:05,840 --> 00:06:06,775
You know what,

115
00:06:06,776 --> 00:06:08,296
Mr. Don't-ask-don't-tell?

116
00:06:09,271 --> 00:06:11,650
You figured out
how to dye that hair of yours

117
00:06:11,695 --> 00:06:13,639
up like a nancy all by yourself,

118
00:06:13,676 --> 00:06:15,430
you sure as hell
can figure out how to get

119
00:06:15,477 --> 00:06:18,059
a prosthetic for that stump
of yours by yourself.

120
00:06:22,691 --> 00:06:26,237
Yeah, I think I got
a pretty good idea where to start.

121
00:06:42,538 --> 00:06:45,839
I'm here with Ed Pavelka, the new warden
of Fox River Penitentiary,

122
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:47,964
where Lincoln Burrows
and Michael Scofield

123
00:06:47,965 --> 00:06:50,512
are scheduled to be returned
to sometime tomorrow.

124
00:06:50,536 --> 00:06:52,257
Now, Warden, the escape happened a mere

125
00:06:52,304 --> 00:06:55,383
two days before Burrows
was scheduled to be put to death.

126
00:06:55,406 --> 00:06:58,887
He's already been granted one day ;
do you anticipate any further?

127
00:06:59,276 --> 00:07:01,387
Lincoln Burrows is a convicted murder.

128
00:07:02,463 --> 00:07:05,838
His escape has endangered the lives
of civilians across this country.

129
00:07:05,839 --> 00:07:07,403
He is not a celebrity.

130
00:07:07,706 --> 00:07:09,150
He is not a martyr.

131
00:07:10,214 --> 00:07:13,150
I can assure you
that whatever leniency was afforded him

132
00:07:13,151 --> 00:07:15,900
and the other prisoners
under the old regime at Fox River

133
00:07:15,901 --> 00:07:17,456
will no longer be tolerated.

134
00:07:17,900 --> 00:07:20,677
The only thing
that Mr. Burrows can expect

135
00:07:20,838 --> 00:07:24,539
is what a jury of his peers demanded:
a speedy execution.

136
00:07:24,713 --> 00:07:26,057
And Michael Scofield?

137
00:07:26,713 --> 00:07:27,713
With his escape,

138
00:07:28,278 --> 00:07:29,777
the aiding and abetting charges,

139
00:07:29,778 --> 00:07:32,111
the felonies he's racked up
along the way,

140
00:07:32,650 --> 00:07:34,213
on top of his original sentence,

141
00:07:34,214 --> 00:07:38,158
I'd say Mr. Scofield will be spending
the rest of his life behind bars.

142
00:07:38,215 --> 00:07:39,215
Thank you.

143
00:08:07,092 --> 00:08:09,923
2x13 - The Killing Box

144
00:08:10,135 --> 00:08:13,255
Transcript: Mickey
Subtitles: www.sub-way.fr (V.1.00)

145
00:08:15,588 --> 00:08:16,588
Who's got Mahone?

146
00:08:20,838 --> 00:08:21,775
<i>Congratulations, sir.</i>

147
00:08:21,776 --> 00:08:22,776
What do you got?

148
00:08:22,965 --> 00:08:24,502
A call from the Illinois DOC.

149
00:08:24,531 --> 00:08:26,797
They're sending a huge contingent
down there to collect

150
00:08:26,841 --> 00:08:29,436
<i>Burrows and Scofield, take them back
to Fox River personally.</i>

151
00:08:29,467 --> 00:08:30,467
<i>Remind them this is</i>

152
00:08:30,507 --> 00:08:32,313
a federal case
and we'll handle the transport.

153
00:08:32,361 --> 00:08:34,889
I did. But it's an election year,
collar this big,

154
00:08:34,929 --> 00:08:36,687
everybody wants a piece.
The warden called

155
00:08:36,757 --> 00:08:39,822
<i>in a favor to the Bureau Chief;
he okayed it, so here we are.</i>

156
00:08:40,086 --> 00:08:41,919
<i>Should be there in about an hour.</i>

157
00:08:42,399 --> 00:08:44,927
I want to be placed
in the prisoner transport vehicle.

158
00:08:45,004 --> 00:08:46,086
What for?

159
00:08:46,151 --> 00:08:47,354
Just get it done.

160
00:08:48,087 --> 00:08:50,000
Sir, these were the big fish.

161
00:08:50,587 --> 00:08:51,864
And you brought 'em in.

162
00:08:52,087 --> 00:08:53,864
You should feel good about that.

163
00:09:00,286 --> 00:09:01,895
We are at least together.

164
00:09:02,073 --> 00:09:03,284
Yes, there is that.

165
00:09:08,007 --> 00:09:09,229
What are you thinking?

166
00:09:09,374 --> 00:09:10,973
I'm thinking about the old man.

167
00:09:12,820 --> 00:09:14,486
What he tried to do, you know.

168
00:09:17,241 --> 00:09:20,241
Tough to go down swinging
when you're locked in a box.

169
00:09:21,930 --> 00:09:23,041
This isn't over yet.

170
00:09:23,305 --> 00:09:24,928
We're entitled to a phone call.

171
00:09:24,929 --> 00:09:27,423
We make that one call to Sara
and if she has the information

172
00:09:27,442 --> 00:09:28,571
dad said she has,

173
00:09:28,744 --> 00:09:31,302
we can get you exonerated
before this whole thing goes down.

174
00:09:35,734 --> 00:09:37,456
We're entitled to a phone call.

175
00:09:37,859 --> 00:09:41,747
You're entitled to precisely squat
until you're officially in custody.

176
00:09:42,109 --> 00:09:44,795
And that won't happen
until you're back in Fox River.

177
00:09:44,796 --> 00:09:45,796
So sit tight.

178
00:09:51,593 --> 00:09:52,796
It's not over yet.

179
00:09:53,297 --> 00:09:54,297
Not yet.

180
00:09:56,171 --> 00:09:59,004
A lot of ground to cover
between here and Illinois.

181
00:09:59,407 --> 00:10:03,318
I mean, what are the chances
we even make it back to Fox River alive?

182
00:10:09,021 --> 00:10:10,629
<i>Saw you on the news, Alex.</i>

183
00:10:10,686 --> 00:10:12,483
- Did you?
<i>- The brothers too.</i>

184
00:10:13,421 --> 00:10:15,087
They were a little more...

185
00:10:15,733 --> 00:10:17,524
breathing than I had hoped.

186
00:10:17,796 --> 00:10:20,303
Yeah, well, Border Patrol showed up.
Nothing I could do.

187
00:10:20,592 --> 00:10:21,632
<i>Really?</i>

188
00:10:22,113 --> 00:10:25,313
Burrows and Scofield, can you see them
from where you are?

189
00:10:26,214 --> 00:10:27,214
Yeah.

190
00:10:27,530 --> 00:10:29,363
<i>Then put a bullet in their heads.</i>

191
00:10:30,590 --> 00:10:31,812
They're being watched.

192
00:10:32,339 --> 00:10:33,339
<i>I don't care.</i>

193
00:10:33,529 --> 00:10:34,694
<i>By armed guards.</i>

194
00:10:34,842 --> 00:10:37,116
They make it back to Fox River,
it is over.

195
00:10:37,215 --> 00:10:38,215
For all of us.

196
00:10:38,478 --> 00:10:41,473
<i>There's not much more this country love
than a bad man with a good story.</i>

197
00:10:41,474 --> 00:10:43,213
How much longer do you think it'll be

198
00:10:43,214 --> 00:10:45,465
before someone puts
a microphone in front of them?

199
00:10:46,031 --> 00:10:46,975
Are you listening?

200
00:10:47,089 --> 00:10:48,588
Okay, with the security here,

201
00:10:48,589 --> 00:10:51,028
what you're asking me to do
is tantamount to suicide.

202
00:10:51,029 --> 00:10:53,650
- Do you understand what I'm saying?
- I wasn't asking anything.

203
00:10:54,468 --> 00:10:56,671
That would imply you had a say
in the matter.

204
00:10:58,840 --> 00:11:01,555
Pull this off and you're halfway home,
Alex.

205
00:11:03,340 --> 00:11:05,673
You remember what home is like.
Don't you?

206
00:11:06,277 --> 00:11:07,388
900 West End Avenue.

207
00:11:07,465 --> 00:11:09,395
White fence. Red door.

208
00:11:09,654 --> 00:11:11,398
Stay away from my family!

209
00:12:09,834 --> 00:12:11,895
You got a little something on your...

210
00:12:12,955 --> 00:12:14,727
No, I... here, let me.

211
00:12:18,715 --> 00:12:21,131
- Pardon my forwardness, I was...
- It's okay. Thank you.

212
00:12:21,468 --> 00:12:23,856
Normally I wouldn't intervene,
it's just...

213
00:12:24,152 --> 00:12:26,529
yesterday when I got home from work,

214
00:12:27,591 --> 00:12:30,368
I found what looked like
the Brazilian Rain Forest

215
00:12:30,465 --> 00:12:32,353
lodged between my two front teeth.

216
00:12:32,988 --> 00:12:34,651
And all I could think about

217
00:12:34,652 --> 00:12:37,540
was the number of people
who must've seen and not...

218
00:12:37,718 --> 00:12:40,495
not a damn one of them
had the decency to tell me.

219
00:12:42,467 --> 00:12:43,612
Mild diastema.

220
00:12:44,654 --> 00:12:45,654
Excuse me?

221
00:12:47,465 --> 00:12:50,020
It's a slight gap between
your eight and nine.

222
00:12:51,465 --> 00:12:52,631
Your two front teeth.

223
00:12:53,217 --> 00:12:56,439
And that it sometimes can act
as a magnet for food like...

224
00:12:57,717 --> 00:13:00,333
broccoli and tuna and sometimes rice.

225
00:13:01,216 --> 00:13:02,216
Or relish.

226
00:13:02,842 --> 00:13:04,230
All this and brains, too?

227
00:13:05,120 --> 00:13:06,705
What are you, a dentist or...?

228
00:13:06,715 --> 00:13:08,619
Me? No, hardly, no.

229
00:13:08,717 --> 00:13:09,717
I could never.

230
00:13:10,403 --> 00:13:12,090
My... ex-husband, he was...

231
00:13:12,091 --> 00:13:13,091
A bastard?

232
00:13:14,719 --> 00:13:15,719
That too.

233
00:13:25,341 --> 00:13:27,498
Have you ever been to Italy, uh...?

234
00:13:28,527 --> 00:13:29,465
Denise.

235
00:13:29,466 --> 00:13:31,205
Denise, that's a lovely name.

236
00:13:35,027 --> 00:13:39,885
You know, in Italy, they have wine
every day with lunch.

237
00:13:41,325 --> 00:13:42,674
And what do we do in this country?

238
00:13:42,712 --> 00:13:45,214
We power our food down with caffeine,
carbonation,

239
00:13:45,215 --> 00:13:46,826
and high fructose corn syrup.

240
00:13:47,778 --> 00:13:51,245
No one ever takes the time
to enjoy things anymore.

241
00:13:55,340 --> 00:14:00,468
Denise, would you do me the honor
of "enjoying"

242
00:14:00,529 --> 00:14:03,229
the rest of your lunch with me?

243
00:14:07,581 --> 00:14:08,876
I think I'd like that.

244
00:14:10,215 --> 00:14:12,237
White or red?

245
00:14:16,054 --> 00:14:19,404
...and with limited financial resources
he poses no flight risk...

246
00:14:19,405 --> 00:14:22,571
Unless he'd rather not stand trial
for capital murder.

247
00:14:23,404 --> 00:14:26,031
The defendant has shown
great resourcefulness

248
00:14:26,090 --> 00:14:29,416
in being able to travel across country
with little money.

249
00:14:29,841 --> 00:14:32,174
There's no reason
he couldn't do it again.

250
00:14:32,719 --> 00:14:36,108
If you don't want to believe me,
believe Mr. Bellick.

251
00:14:39,028 --> 00:14:40,583
<i>You thieving son of a bitch.</i>

252
00:14:40,642 --> 00:14:42,664
